 {"attack_stage": ["none", "reconnaissance", "initial_access", "persistence", "command_and_control"], "attack_type": ["normal", "port_scan", "exploit", "backdoor", "trojan_callback", "c2", "other_attack"], "category": "attack_types", "chunk_id": "attack_type_mapping__chunk_001", "doc_id": "attack_type_mapping", "keywords": ["attack_type", "taxonomy", "normal", "exploit", "c2"], "source_file": "rag/knowledge/attack_types/attack_type_mapping.md", "text": "# Attack type mapping policy\n\n## Evidence\n\nEvent cards should be mapped to the smallest supported attack_type that is directly supported by evidence. The output vocabulary is closed: normal, port_scan, exploit, backdoor, trojan_callback, c2, and other_attack.\n\n## Judgment\n\nUse port_scan for scanning evidence, exploit for vulnerability-use evidence, backdoor for implant access, trojan_callback for malware calling home, c2 for established command-and-control, and other_attack only when strong attack evidence does not fit the main classes.\n\n## Stage mapping\n\nThe stage should follow the observed behavior, not the file source. Reconnaissance maps to discovery, initial_access to attempted entry, persistence to durable access, command_and_control to remote control, and none to benign or insufficient evidence.\n\n## Boundaries\n\nDo not use other_attack as a synonym for uncertain. If evidence is weak or missing, prefer normal with low confidence and explain the missing evidence.", "title": "Attack type mapping policy"}
 {"attack_stage": ["persistence", "command_and_control"], "attack_type": ["backdoor"], "category": "attack_types", "chunk_id": "backdoor_detection__chunk_001", "doc_id": "backdoor_detection", "keywords": ["backdoor", "implant", "beacon", "shell", "DOUBLEPULSAR"], "source_file": "rag/knowledge/attack_types/backdoor_detection.md", "text": "# Backdoor detection\n\n## Evidence\n\nBackdoor evidence includes implant beacons, unauthorized remote shell behavior, suspicious listener access, or signatures naming a backdoor family or post-exploitation implant.\n\n## Judgment\n\nUse backdoor when evidence points to a persistent or implanted access mechanism. If the behavior is only a callback from a Trojan, trojan_callback may be narrower.\n\n## Stage mapping\n\nBackdoor traffic can map to persistence when it indicates durable access, or command_and_control when it shows active remote control.\n\n## Boundaries\n\nA successful connection to an admin service is not automatically a backdoor. Require implant, unauthorized shell, or backdoor-specific signature evidence.", "title": "Backdoor detection"}
 {"attack_stage": ["initial_access"], "attack_type": ["other_attack"], "category": "attack_types", "chunk_id": "bruteforce_detection__chunk_001", "doc_id": "bruteforce_detection", "keywords": ["bruteforce", "SSH", "FTP", "RDP", "login failures", "authentication"], "source_file": "rag/knowledge/attack_types/bruteforce_detection.md", "text": "# Bruteforce detection\n\n## Evidence\n\nBruteforce evidence includes many authentication attempts, repeated failures, many usernames, or IDS signatures naming SSH, FTP, web, or RDP brute force.\n\n## Judgment\n\nThe supported attack_type vocabulary has no dedicated brute_force label, so classify strong brute-force evidence as other_attack with subtype brute_force.\n\n## Stage mapping\n\nBruteforce normally maps to initial_access because it attempts to gain entry through credentials.\n\n## Boundaries\n\nRepeated failed connections are not always authentication failures. Confirm that the protocol and evidence actually involve login attempts.", "title": "Bruteforce detection"}
-{"attack_stage": ["command_and_control"], "attack_type": ["c2"], "category": "attack_types", "chunk_id": "c2_detection__chunk_001", "doc_id": "c2_detection", "keywords": ["C2", "CnC", "beacon", "checkin", "botnet", "command_and_control"], "source_file": "rag/knowledge/attack_types/c2_detection.md", "text": "# C2 detection\n\n## Evidence\n\nC2 evidence includes malware checkin signatures, beacon-like periodicity, suspicious external domains, repeated small connections, botnet categories, or known command-and-control protocol indicators.\n\n## Judgment\n\nClassify as c2 when the event suggests an established channel for remote instructions or status exchange. Strong Suricata categories such as Malware Command and Control Activity can carry high weight.\n\n## Stage mapping\n\nC2 maps to command_and_control because the traffic supports remote coordination after compromise.\n\n## Boundaries\n\nPeriodic traffic alone is not proof of C2. Combine timing with domain reputation, alert signature, protocol behavior, payload hints, or unusual destination context.", "title": "C2 detection"}
+{"attack_stage": ["command_and_control"], "attack_type": ["c2"], "category": "attack_types", "chunk_id": "c2_detection__chunk_001", "doc_id": "c2_detection", "keywords": ["C2", "CnC", "beacon", "checkin", "botnet", "command_and_control"], "source_file": "rag/knowledge/attack_types/c2_detection.md", "text": "# C2 detection\n\n## Evidence\n\nC2 evidence includes malware checkin signatures, beacon-like periodicity, suspicious external domains, repeated small connections, botnet categories, or known command-and-control protocol indicators.\n\n## Judgment\n\nClassify as C2-like behavior when repeated outbound sessions suggest an established channel for remote instructions or status exchange. Require multiple corroborating connection, timing, service, DNS, HTTP, or TLS indicators.\n\n## Stage mapping\n\nC2 maps to command_and_control because the traffic supports remote coordination after compromise.\n\n## Boundaries\n\nPeriodic traffic alone is not proof of C2. Combine timing with domain reputation, alert signature, protocol behavior, payload hints, or unusual destination context.", "title": "C2 detection"}
 {"attack_stage": ["command_and_control"], "attack_type": ["other_attack"], "category": "attack_types", "chunk_id": "data_exfiltration_detection__chunk_001", "doc_id": "data_exfiltration_detection", "keywords": ["exfiltration", "large outbound", "DNS tunnel", "HTTP upload", "data transfer"], "source_file": "rag/knowledge/attack_types/data_exfiltration_detection.md", "text": "# Data exfiltration detection\n\n## Evidence\n\nExfiltration evidence includes unusual outbound volume, suspicious upload paths, DNS tunneling patterns, or alerts naming data leakage and covert channels.\n\n## Judgment\n\nWith the current closed vocabulary, strong exfiltration evidence should be other_attack with subtype data_exfiltration unless it is better described as c2.\n\n## Stage mapping\n\nExfiltration often occurs after access and may share infrastructure with command_and_control, so use command_and_control when the event is outbound coordination or covert transfer.\n\n## Boundaries\n\nNormal uploads and cloud synchronization can be large. Require unusual destination, protocol misuse, alert context, or clear covert-channel indicators.", "title": "Data exfiltration detection"}
 {"attack_stage": ["initial_access"], "attack_type": ["other_attack"], "category": "attack_types", "chunk_id": "dos_ddos_detection__chunk_001", "doc_id": "dos_ddos_detection", "keywords": ["DoS", "DDoS", "flood", "SYN flood", "high_volume_activity"], "source_file": "rag/knowledge/attack_types/dos_ddos_detection.md", "text": "# DoS and DDoS detection\n\n## Evidence\n\nDoS evidence includes extreme packet or connection volume, many sources hitting one service, repeated reset or timeout states, and signatures naming floods or denial-of-service behavior.\n\n## Judgment\n\nBecause the closed attack_type set has no dos label, classify strong DoS evidence as other_attack with subtype dos_ddos.\n\n## Stage mapping\n\nDoS does not fit neatly into the listed stages; use initial_access when the event is an active attack against availability, and explain the mapping.\n\n## Boundaries\n\nHigh volume alone is not enough. Large file transfers, backups, or scans can be noisy; require flood pattern, service impact indicators, or IDS support.", "title": "DoS and DDoS detection"}
-{"attack_stage": ["initial_access"], "attack_type": ["exploit"], "category": "attack_types", "chunk_id": "exploit_detection__chunk_001", "doc_id": "exploit_detection", "keywords": ["exploit", "vulnerability", "CVE", "initial_access", "alert"], "source_file": "rag/knowledge/attack_types/exploit_detection.md", "text": "# Exploit detection\n\n## Evidence\n\nExploit evidence can come from IDS signatures, protocol-specific vulnerability indicators, suspicious payload paths, abnormal SMB or web requests, or known exploit names in Suricata signatures.\n\n## Judgment\n\nClassify as exploit when the event shows an attempted use of a vulnerability or exploit technique. Prefer concrete evidence such as signature names, affected protocol, target port, and payload context.\n\n## Stage mapping\n\nExploit attempts generally map to initial_access because they seek to enter, execute code, or gain unauthorized capability on the target.\n\n## Boundaries\n\nDo not infer exploit from a service port alone. Port 445, 80, or 443 is common in normal traffic; require vulnerability-specific evidence or strong suspicious request patterns.", "title": "Exploit detection"}
+{"attack_stage": ["initial_access"], "attack_type": ["exploit"], "category": "attack_types", "chunk_id": "exploit_detection__chunk_001", "doc_id": "exploit_detection", "keywords": ["exploit", "vulnerability", "CVE", "initial_access", "alert"], "source_file": "rag/knowledge/attack_types/exploit_detection.md", "text": "# Exploit detection\n\n## Evidence\n\nExploit evidence can come from protocol-specific vulnerability indicators, suspicious payload paths, abnormal SMB or web requests, known CVE/probe strings, or exploit-consistent responses.\n\n## Judgment\n\nClassify as exploit when the event shows an attempted use of a vulnerability or exploit technique. Prefer concrete evidence such as signature names, affected protocol, target port, and payload context.\n\n## Stage mapping\n\nExploit attempts generally map to initial_access because they seek to enter, execute code, or gain unauthorized capability on the target.\n\n## Boundaries\n\nDo not infer exploit from a service port alone. Port 445, 80, or 443 is common in normal traffic; require vulnerability-specific evidence or strong suspicious request patterns.", "title": "Exploit detection"}
 {"attack_stage": ["none", "reconnaissance", "initial_access", "persistence", "command_and_control"], "attack_type": ["other_attack"], "category": "attack_types", "chunk_id": "other_attack_policy__chunk_001", "doc_id": "other_attack_policy", "keywords": ["other_attack", "policy", "uncertain", "closed vocabulary"], "source_file": "rag/knowledge/attack_types/other_attack_policy.md", "text": "# Other attack policy\n\n## Evidence\n\nother_attack is for clear malicious or attack-like evidence that does not fit normal, port_scan, exploit, backdoor, trojan_callback, or c2.\n\n## Judgment\n\nUse other_attack sparingly and name the subtype, such as brute_force, dos_ddos, web_attack, protocol_abuse, or data_exfiltration. If evidence is insufficient, choose normal instead.\n\n## Stage mapping\n\nThe stage should still be selected from the closed stage list according to behavior.\n\n## Boundaries\n\nDo not hide uncertainty in other_attack. Low evidence belongs in normal/none with low confidence and a direct evidence statement.", "title": "Other attack policy"}
 {"attack_stage": ["reconnaissance"], "attack_type": ["port_scan"], "category": "attack_types", "chunk_id": "port_scan_detection__chunk_001", "doc_id": "port_scan_detection", "keywords": ["port_scan", "Nmap", "SYN", "unique_dst_ports", "failed_conn_rate"], "source_file": "rag/knowledge/attack_types/port_scan_detection.md", "text": "# Port scan detection\n\n## Evidence\n\nA port scan often appears as many connection attempts from one source toward many destination ports or hosts. Useful features include high unique_dst_ports, high tcp_syn_count, low tcp_ack_count, many Zeek S0 or REJ states, and high failed_conn_rate.\n\n## Judgment\n\nWhen the main evidence is systematic probing rather than exploitation, classify as port_scan. A single blocked connection is not enough; the pattern should show breadth, repetition, or scanning-like sequencing.\n\n## Stage mapping\n\nPort scanning normally maps to reconnaissance because the actor is discovering exposed services before choosing an entry point.\n\n## Boundaries\n\nHigh volume alone is not always a scan. Backup jobs, monitoring systems, or service discovery can touch many hosts; require scan-like port or host diversity and failed connection evidence.", "title": "Port scan detection"}
 {"attack_stage": ["initial_access"], "attack_type": ["exploit"], "category": "attack_types", "chunk_id": "smb_exploit_detection__chunk_001", "doc_id": "smb_exploit_detection", "keywords": ["SMB", "SMBv1", "MS17-010", "EternalBlue", "port 445", "port 139"], "source_file": "rag/knowledge/attack_types/smb_exploit_detection.md", "text": "# SMB exploit detection\n\n## Evidence\n\nSMB exploit evidence includes traffic to ports 445 or 139 combined with exploit signatures, SMBv1 behavior, MS17-010 references, malformed transaction patterns, or related IDS alerts.\n\n## Judgment\n\nClassify as exploit when SMB evidence points to vulnerability use rather than ordinary file sharing. The subtype can be smb_exploit or ms17_010 when the signature explicitly supports it.\n\n## Stage mapping\n\nSMB exploitation maps to initial_access because it targets a network service to gain unauthorized execution or access.\n\n## Boundaries\n\nSMB traffic is common in Windows networks. Do not treat port 445 alone as exploit; require exploit signature, suspicious SMB operation, or strong anomaly context.", "title": "SMB exploit detection"}
 {"attack_stage": ["command_and_control"], "attack_type": ["trojan_callback"], "category": "attack_types", "chunk_id": "trojan_callback_detection__chunk_001", "doc_id": "trojan_callback_detection", "keywords": ["trojan", "callback", "malware download", "phone home", "HTTP callback"], "source_file": "rag/knowledge/attack_types/trojan_callback_detection.md", "text": "# Trojan callback detection\n\n## Evidence\n\nTrojan callback evidence includes malware-family alerts, suspicious HTTP or TLS outbound contact, file retrieval followed by callback, or signatures describing a Trojan checkin.\n\n## Judgment\n\nUse trojan_callback when the evidence emphasizes malware calling home rather than a general-purpose C2 channel. If the signature explicitly says CnC or botnet, c2 may be more precise.\n\n## Stage mapping\n\nMost callbacks map to command_and_control because the compromised host is contacting external infrastructure.\n\n## Boundaries\n\nDo not classify ordinary software update checks as trojan_callback without malware-specific signatures or suspicious domain, URI, or payload evidence.", "title": "Trojan callback detection"}
-{"attack_stage": ["initial_access"], "attack_type": ["exploit"], "category": "attack_types", "chunk_id": "web_exploit_detection__chunk_001", "doc_id": "web_exploit_detection", "keywords": ["web exploit", "SQL injection", "XSS", "directory traversal", "command injection", "http.request.uri"], "source_file": "rag/knowledge/attack_types/web_exploit_detection.md", "text": "# Web exploit detection\n\n## Evidence\n\nWeb exploit candidates often include suspicious HTTP URI patterns, encoded traversal strings, SQL operators, script tags, shell metacharacters, unusual methods, or Suricata web attack categories.\n\n## Judgment\n\nIf HTTP evidence indicates an attempt to abuse a web application vulnerability, classify as exploit and set subtype to the specific family when possible, such as sql_injection, xss, directory_traversal, or command_injection.\n\n## Stage mapping\n\nWeb exploitation maps to initial_access when it attempts to compromise the application or server.\n\n## Boundaries\n\nBenign scanners, crawlers, and malformed URLs can resemble web attacks. Use alert signatures, repeated attempts, and dangerous parameters to raise confidence.", "title": "Web exploit detection"}
+{"attack_stage": ["initial_access"], "attack_type": ["exploit"], "category": "attack_types", "chunk_id": "web_exploit_detection__chunk_001", "doc_id": "web_exploit_detection", "keywords": ["web exploit", "SQL injection", "XSS", "directory traversal", "command injection", "http.request.uri"], "source_file": "rag/knowledge/attack_types/web_exploit_detection.md", "text": "# Web exploit detection\n\n## Evidence\n\nWeb exploit candidates often include suspicious HTTP URI patterns, encoded traversal strings, SQL operators, script tags, shell metacharacters, unusual methods, or abnormal HTTP response behavior.\n\n## Judgment\n\nIf HTTP evidence indicates an attempt to abuse a web application vulnerability, classify as exploit and set subtype to the specific family when possible, such as sql_injection, xss, directory_traversal, or command_injection.\n\n## Stage mapping\n\nWeb exploitation maps to initial_access when it attempts to compromise the application or server.\n\n## Boundaries\n\nBenign scanners, crawlers, and malformed URLs can resemble web attacks. Use alert signatures, repeated attempts, and dangerous parameters to raise confidence.", "title": "Web exploit detection"}
 {"attack_stage": ["initial_access"], "attack_type": ["other_attack"], "category": "competition_labels", "chunk_id": "competition_TA01_01_bruteforce__chunk_001", "doc_id": "competition_TA01_01_bruteforce", "keywords": ["TA01_01", "TA01", "brute force", "bruteforce", "password attack", "login failures", "SSH", "FTP", "RDP", "authentication"], "source_file": "rag/knowledge/competition_labels/TA01_01_bruteforce.md", "text": "# TA01_01 password brute force\n\nUse `TA01_01` when the record shows repeated attempts to authenticate to a service. Strong evidence includes many failed logins, repeated SSH/FTP/RDP/SMB/HTTP-login sessions, authentication brute-force signatures, many short login attempts, or a high failed-attempt ratio against the same service.\n\n`TA01_01` is initial access. It should map to stage `TA01`.\n\n# Normal and background avoidance\n\nDo not classify one or two failed logins, ordinary retries, reset-heavy but non-authentication traffic, or missing-payload flow rows as brute force by default.\n\nIf the record has only weak generic connection failures and no authentication context, prefer `TN01_01`.\n\n# Boundary cues\n\nPrefer `TA01_02` when the evidence is exploit payload or vulnerability exploitation rather than repeated credential attempts.\n\nPrefer `TN01_01` for isolated failed business access or low-signal flow-only records.", "title": "TA01_01 password brute force"}
 {"attack_stage": ["initial_access"], "attack_type": ["exploit"], "category": "competition_labels", "chunk_id": "competition_TA01_02_exploit__chunk_001", "doc_id": "competition_TA01_02_exploit", "keywords": ["TA01_02", "TA01", "exploit", "vulnerability exploitation", "command injection", "SQL injection", "XSS", "SMB exploit", "payload"], "source_file": "rag/knowledge/competition_labels/TA01_02_exploit.md", "text": "# TA01_02 vulnerability exploitation\n\nUse `TA01_02` when the record contains evidence of an exploitation attempt against a vulnerable service. Strong evidence includes exploit-specific alerts, command injection strings, SQL injection or XSS payloads, SMB exploit indicators, directory traversal payloads, web exploit attempts, or protocol behavior consistent with attempted compromise.\n\n`TA01_02` is initial access. It should map to stage `TA01`.\n\n# Normal and background avoidance\n\nDo not classify normal application errors, generic web requests, ordinary high-volume browsing, or scanner-only enumeration as exploitation without payload or exploit-specific evidence.\n\nFlow-only exploit labels can support secondary evaluation, but payload-bearing PCAP or protocol evidence is stronger.\n\n# Boundary cues\n\nPrefer `TA43_02` when the record is vulnerability probing or version enumeration without exploitation payload.\n\nPrefer `TA03_01` only when the evidence moves from exploitation into installation or persistence.", "title": "TA01_02 vulnerability exploitation"}
 {"attack_stage": ["persistence"], "attack_type": ["backdoor"], "category": "competition_labels", "chunk_id": "competition_TA03_01_backdoor_install__chunk_001", "doc_id": "competition_TA03_01_backdoor_install", "keywords": ["TA03_01", "TA03", "backdoor install", "implant", "persistence", "dropper", "webshell upload", "service creation", "autorun"], "source_file": "rag/knowledge/competition_labels/TA03_01_backdoor_install.md", "text": "# TA03_01 backdoor installation\n\nUse `TA03_01` when the record evidence indicates installation or creation of durable unauthorized access. Strong evidence includes webshell upload or placement, implant or dropper delivery, service creation, scheduled task or autorun persistence, backdoor file transfer, or alerts that explicitly describe implant/persistence installation.\n\n`TA03_01` is persistence. It should map to stage `TA03`.\n\n# Normal and background avoidance\n\nDo not classify ordinary file downloads, software updates, normal admin transfers, generic malware callback traffic, or exploit attempts without installation evidence as `TA03_01`.\n\nIf the record only shows command-and-control check-ins after compromise, prefer a TA11 code.\n\n# Boundary cues\n\nPrefer `TA11_01` when the evidence is interactive access to an already installed backdoor.\n\nPrefer `TA11_02` when the evidence is outbound malware callback, beaconing, or check-in traffic.\n\nPrefer `TA01_02` when the evidence is exploitation but persistence is not shown.", "title": "TA03_01 backdoor installation"}
